$$ \frac{{\partial C}} {{\partial t}} + {\text{u}} \cdot \nabla C = - D\nabla ^2 C $$\end{document} where C is the concentration of species, u is the velocity vector and D is the diffusivity of species in the blood.

LDL transport was modelled as a concentration polarisation effect, a phenomenon which has been demonstrated to occur in large and medium sized arteries.5,11,39Concentration polarisation is the accumulation and elevation of endothelial surface concentration of LDL due to plasma filtration through the semi permeable endothelium. LDL mass transport boundary conditions applied in this study were uniform inlet concentration, Co (=1.2 mg/ml of blood),36 a zero gradient in concentration at the outlet and mass conservation of LDL at the luminal surface of the endothelium39 described as 5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
